 <h2>FAQ</h2>
 <h3>What makes New York-style pizza unique?</h3>
 <p>New York-style pizza is known for its thin, foldable crust. It has tangy tomato sauce and lots of toppings. This mix of ingredients and baking methods makes it special.</p>
 <h3>What type of flour is best for making New York-style pizza dough?</h3>
 <p>High-protein bread flour is the top choice for New York-style pizza dough. It makes the crust chewy and pliable. All-purpose flour works too, but the dough might not be as elastic.</p>
 <h3>How important is the water temperature when making New York-style pizza dough?</h3>
 <p>Water temperature is key for making the dough right. It should be between 110-115°F (43-46°C). This helps the yeast work well and gets the dough just right.</p>
 <h3>What type of cheese is best for New York-style pizza?</h3>
 <p>Low-moisture mozzarella is the go-to cheese for New York-style pizza. It melts well and adds great flavor. Grated or shredded mozzarella is best for that authentic taste.</p>
 <h3>How do I achieve the perfect crust when baking New York-style pizza?</h3>
 <p>For a perfect crust, preheat your oven to 500°F (260°C). Use a pizza stone or steel to cook it. Stretch and shape the dough right to get that perfect crust.</p>
 <h3>What are some common mistakes to avoid when making New York-style pizza at home?</h3>
 <p>Don't overwork the dough or use the wrong cheese. Make sure your oven is hot enough and don't overbake. Using the right ingredients and techniques is key for a real New York-style pizza.</p>